        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                    <p><img src="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8/01-2.png" class="type:primaryImage" alt="" /></p>
                <h2>One of the earliest steam railways in the world</h2>
<p><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;">An image representing July 17</span><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: xx-small;"><sup>th</sup></span><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;"> 1832.<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>A celebration for the opening of the railway from Leicester to Bagworth. The railway provided passenger and freight services.<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>Its main purpose; to transport coal from the burgeoning<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>Leicestershire coalfield.</span></p>
<h2>The Bagworth incline...</h2>
<figure class="post__image"><img loading="lazy"  src="file:///Users/haideral-delfi/Documents/Publii/sites/bagworth/input/media/posts/6//02.png" alt="" width="694" height="383" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="file:///Users/haideral-delfi/Documents/Publii/sites/bagworth/input/media/posts/6//responsive/02-xs.png 300w ,file:///Users/haideral-delfi/Documents/Publii/sites/bagworth/input/media/posts/6//responsive/02-sm.png 480w ,file:///Users/haideral-delfi/Documents/Publii/sites/bagworth/input/media/posts/6//responsive/02-md.png 768w"></figure>
<p><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;">Walk down Park Lane, by the Bagworth allotments, cross the railway bridge and turn right down the obvious footpath.<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>You are standing at the top of the Bagworth incline; the original course of the railway.<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>The railway was rerouted to its current path in xxxx.</span></p>
<h2>... and the Roundhouse</h2>
<figure class="post__image"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//03.png" alt="" width="696" height="432" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/03-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/03-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/03-md.png 768w"></figure>
<p><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;">Continue your walk for a short distance and obvious pile of rubble on the left is all that remains of the Bagworth Winding House known as the Round House.<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>Here heavy ropes looped around a pulley to allow gravity, and the heavily laden trucks, to pull the empty trucks back up the incline.</span></p>
<h2>A Rerouting</h2>
<figure class="post__image"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//04.png" alt="" width="696" height="392" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/04-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/04-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/04-md.png 768w"></figure>
<p><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;">The use of the incline was never fully satisfactory and in 1848 the line was rerouted with gradient minimised by embankments and road bridges to its present path.</span></p>
<h2>A close encounter</h2>
<figure class="post__image"><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;"><span class="Apple-converted-space"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//05.png" alt="" width="907" height="512" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/05-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/05-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/05-md.png 768w"></figure></span></span></p>
<p><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;">The colliery sidings left the main railway close to Bagworth and Ellistown Station at the end of Railway Terrace,<span class="Apple-converted-space">  </span>crossing Station Road near to the allotment gates.</span></p>
<h2>Locomotives</h2>
<figure class="post__image"><img loading="lazy"  src="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//06.png" alt="" width="703" height="458" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/06-xs.png 300w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/06-sm.png 480w ,https://bagworth.org.uk/media/posts/8//responsive/06-md.png 768w"></figure>
<p><span style="color: #000000; font-family: Helvetica; font-size: medium;">The first locomotives, Comet and Phoenix, were primitive steam engines which lacked the power to climb the incline without assistance</span></p>
            ]]>
        </content>
